1. Install the required SELinux packages.
Solution:
Got it ✅ — installing SELinux packages is a common hardening/configuration task in Linux (especially on RHEL/CentOS-based systems).
Here’s how you can install them step by step:
Check Current SELinux Status:
sestatus
If the command is not found, it means SELinux tools are not installed — so we proceed with installation.
Install SELinux Packages:
sudo yum install -y policycoreutils selinux-policy selinux-policy-targeted policycoreutils-python-utils

Rocky Linux / AlmaLinux:
sudo dnf install -y policycoreutils selinux-policy selinux-policy-targeted policycoreutils-python-utils

Ubuntu:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y selinux-basics selinux-policy-default auditd
Enable SELinux (If Required):
sudo vi /etc/selinux/config
Reboot:
sudo reboot

STatus check: sestatus

2. Permanently disable SELinux for the time being; it will be re-enabled after necessary configuration changes.
sestatus

sudo vi /etc/selinux/config


3. No need to reboot the server, as a scheduled maintenance reboot is already planned for tonight.

4. Disregard the current status of SELinux via the command line; the final status after the reboot should be disabled.
